{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_0","type":"agent_message","text":"# Arbiter Ruling\n\n## Amendment: CLI-RUN-WRITER-LOCK\n\n### Ruling\nACCEPT\n\n### Rationale\nBoth planners and reviewers agree this is a real race condition: CLI `start`/`resume` paths call the engine without acquiring the writer lock, while daemon paths do. The read-before-write state check in CLI is non-atomic, so concurrent invocations can interleave and corrupt run/task state. Enforcing the same locking protocol in CLI is required to preserve one-writer invariants.\n\n## Amendment: DAEMON-PROCESS-GLOBAL-CWD\n\n### Ruling\nACCEPT\n\n### Rationale\nAll parties agree this is unsafe in a multi-threaded runtime: mutating process-wide CWD with `set_current_dir` is global mutable state and can race across concurrent workers. Panic/unwind can also skip restoration, and the engine already passes explicit root/dir context for operations. Removing global cwd mutation (or fully RAII-guarding it as fallback) is correct.\n\n## Amendment: STRAY-SCHEDULED-TASKS-LOCK\n\n### Ruling\nACCEPT\n\n### Rationale\nTracking `.claude/scheduled_tasks.lock` is clearly incorrect for source control: it contains ephemeral session/PID metadata and is not project code or reproducible state. This should be removed from the repository and ignored in `.gitignore`/cleanup rules to avoid stale lock leakage in version history.\n\n## Amendment: AM-001\n\n### Ruling\nREJECT\n\n### Rationale\nAM-001 is materially the same defect as `DAEMON-PROCESS-GLOBAL-CWD`, with the same location and remediation goal. Accepting both as separate amendments risks redundant/overlapping change management. The fix should be captured under `DAEMON-PROCESS-GLOBAL-CWD` only.\n\n## Amendment: AM-002\n\n### Ruling\nACCEPT\n\n### Rationale\nThe daemon currently escalates transient per-task journal write failures into a full daemon termination via `?` propagation, leaving claimed tasks and leases in a partially-failed state. Treating claim-write failures as isolated task failures (rather than crashing the whole process) is a robustness improvement with clear correctness and availability benefits.\n\n## Amendment: AM-003\n\n### Ruling\nACCEPT\n\n### Rationale\nReleasing errors are swallowed while the reconcile report still marks leases as released, creating inaccurate operational visibility and potentially masking leaked worktrees/locks. Updating reporting logic to only mark successful releases restores correctness and improves diagnosability; this is a straightforward, low-risk fix.\n\n## Amendment: AM-004\n\n### Ruling\nACCEPT\n\n### Rationale\nRuntime-generated logs under `.ralph/tmp/logs` are environment artifacts and should not be committed. Adding ignore rules and removing previously tracked runtime files is valid repository hygiene that reduces noisy diffs and prevents accidental persistence of ephemeral execution state."}}
